<h2> Introduction:</h2>

This lab provides experience with strings.

<h2> Lab Assignment:</h2>

<h4> Problem Motivation and Definition:</h4>

Text strings are one of the fundamental data structures in computer science
theory and practice.
<br>In C++ there are two kinds of strings:
<ul>
    <li><u>C strings</u> which are essentially character arrays,
	left justified, with the logical string terminated by the <tt>null</tt> character.
	<li><u>string class</u> objects which are a much safer and more
	user-friendly special type from the C++ Standard Library.
</ul>

Modern data processing consists mostly of string processing.  And, it's string processing that is often a source of trouble in development and maintenance.

<h4> Solution Specification:</h4>
<ol>
    <li> Create a new directory, <tt>lab10</tt>, and move to it.

    <li> For the following tasks, perform the task <i>twice</i>
    - once using C-strings, and again using string class strings.

    <li> Create and test a function that <i>centers</i> one string in a second empty sting having a given <u>width</u>.
    Padding with be with blanks.<br>
    Return <tt>false</tt> if the width is too small, else <tt>true</tt>.

    <li> Write a function which detects
    <a href="http://www.palindromelist.com">palindromes</a>
    such as "<i>Madam, I'm Adam</i>".<br>
    Create and test a function which detects palindromes returning <tt>true</tt>
    if a string is a palindrome and <tt>false</tt> otherwise.<br>
    Capitalization, punctuation, and spacing are to be ignored.

    <li> When correct, generate via <tt>enscript</tt> an HTML printout of the
    sources, and demonstrate, via <tt>script</tt>, the sources and the
    running of the program data.<br>
    Submit to D2L.
</ol>

